  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And they caused their sons and their daughters to pass through the fire.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (On this phrase, see the comment upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The sin of child-murder had not Been previously laid to the charge of Israel; but, as it had infected Judah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), there is no reason why it should not have invaded also the sister kingdom. Perhaps it is alluded to by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 5:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and Hosea 6:8. It was an old sin of the Canaanitish nations (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 18:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), and continued to be practiced by the Moabites (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 3:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and Ammonites, neighbors of Israel. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And used divination and enchantments.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The \"witchcrafts\" of Jezebel have been already mentioned (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 9:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Magical practices always accompanied idolatry, and were of many kinds. Sometimes divination was by means of staves or rods (rhabdomancy), which were manipulated in various ways (Herod., 4:67; Schol. ad Nicandr., 'Theriac.,' 613; Tacit., 'German.,' § 10; Atom. Marc., 31:2; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Sometimes it was by arrows (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezekiel 21:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Very often, especially in Greece and Rome, it was by inspecting the entrails of victims. Where faith in God wanes, a trust in magical practices, astrology, chiromancy, \"sertes Virgilianae,\" horoscopes, spirit-rapping, and the like, almost always supervenes. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And sold themselves to do evil in the sight of the Lord, to provoke him to anger.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (On the expression, \"sold themselves to do evil,\" see the comment upon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 21:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) 2 Kings 17:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The climax of their apostasy: \"They made themselves molten images, two (golden) calves\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 12:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which are called מסּכה after ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 32:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"and Asherah,\" i.e., idols of Astarte (for the fact, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"and worshipped all the host of heaven (sun, moon, and stars), and served Baal\" - in the time of Ahab and his family (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 16:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The worshipping of all the host of heaven is not specially mentioned in the history of the kingdom of the ten tribes, but occurs first of all in Judah in the time of Manasseh (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The fact that the host of heaven is mentioned between Asherah and Baal shows that the historian refers to the Baal and Astarte worship, and has borrowed the expression from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
